# Git & PR Workflow

## Committing

- Use `scripts/committer "<msg>" <file...>` to create commits — avoid manual `git add`/`git commit`.
- Concise, action-oriented commit messages: `CLI: add verbose flag to send`.
- Group related changes; avoid bundling unrelated refactors.

## Multi-Agent Safety

These rules are critical when multiple AI agents may be working on the repo:
- Do NOT create/apply/drop `git stash` entries unless explicitly requested.
- Do NOT create/remove/modify `git worktree` unless explicitly requested.
- Do NOT switch branches unless explicitly requested.
- On `push`: may `git pull --rebase` but never discard other agents' work.
- On `commit`: scope to your changes only. On `commit all`: commit everything in grouped chunks.
- When you see unrecognized files, keep going — focus on your changes.

## PR Rules

- One PR = one issue/topic. Do not mix unrelated concerns.
- PRs over ~5,000 changed lines are reviewed only in exceptional circumstances.
- PR submission template: `.github/pull_request_template.md`.
- Mark AI-assisted PRs in title/description.

## Pre-commit Hooks

- Install: `prek install`
- Runs: trailing-whitespace, detect-secrets, shellcheck, oxlint, oxfmt, swiftlint, swiftformat, ruff.
- Lint/format churn: if diffs are formatting-only, auto-resolve without asking.

## Changelog

- User-facing changes only; no internal/meta notes.
- Pure test additions/fixes do NOT need a changelog entry.

## Shorthand: `sync`

If working tree is dirty, commit all changes (sensible Conventional Commit message), then `git pull --rebase`; if rebase conflicts and cannot resolve, stop; otherwise `git push`.
